<subSubSection lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1437,1699,2013]" lastBlockId="36.[151,1436,151,249]" lastPageId="36" lastPageNumber="37" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Karyotype: 2n = 48 and FN = 54. Autosomal complement: four small metacentric and submetacentric pairs, and 19 acrocentric pairs (one large and the remaining medium to small decreasing in size). Sex chromosomes: X, a medium subtelocentric; Y, a small acrocentric (
<figureCitation box="[671,760,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1382,1406]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,286,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[151,1436,273,1321]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 9. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 1, male with 2n = 48 and FN = 54. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 112); (B) C-banding (JAP 112); (C) G-banding (JAP 112); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 112)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423637" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423637/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
). C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes. The X chromosome presented the short arm entirely heterochromatic. The Y chromosome was almost entirely heterochromatic (
<figureCitation box="[1002,1091,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1382,1406]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,286,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[151,1436,273,1321]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 9. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 1, male with 2n = 48 and FN = 54. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 112); (B) C-banding (JAP 112); (C) G-banding (JAP 112); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 112)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423637" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423637/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). G-banding was performed to allow the correct identification of all homologous pairs (
<figureCitation box="[787,876,1915,1941]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1382,1406]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,286,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[151,1436,273,1321]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 9. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 1, male with 2n = 48 and FN = 54. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 112); (B) C-banding (JAP 112); (C) G-banding (JAP 112); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 112)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423637" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423637/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
). FISH with telomeric sequences revealed signals exclusively at the ends of all chromosome arms and no interstitial signals were observed (
<figureCitation box="[1158,1248,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1382,1406]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,286,1314]" captionTargetId="figure-61@36.[151,1436,273,1321]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 9. Karyotype of Neacomys sp. 1, male with 2n = 48 and FN = 54. (A) Conventional staining (JAP 112); (B) C-banding (JAP 112); (C) G-banding (JAP 112); (D) Metaphase plate after fluorescent in situ hybridization with telomeric probe (left) and DAPI staining (right) (JAP 112)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423637" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423637/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 9D</figureCitation>
). This karyotype seems to be the same reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sanchez-Vendizu, P. &amp; Pacheco, V. &amp; Vivas-Ruiz, D." box="[536,878,1987,2013]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="1 - 39" refId="ref73116" refString="Sanchez-Vendizu, P., Pacheco, V. &amp; Vivas-Ruiz, D. (2018) An Introduction to the Systematics of Small-Bodied Neacomys (Rodentia: Cricetidae) from Peru with Descriptions of Two New Species. American Museum Novitates, 3913, 1 - 39. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 3913.1" type="journal article" year="2018">
Sánchez-Vendizú 
<emphasis box="[738,788,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">et al</emphasis>
. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sanchez-Vendizu, Pacheco &amp; Vivas-Ruiz" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[926,1079,1987,2013]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Neacomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rosalindae">
<emphasis box="[926,1079,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">N. rosalindae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, these authors appar-ently misclassified two small metacentric pairs as acrocentric. Also, the X chromosome seems to present two different morphologies, a medium submetacentric or subtelocentric. A morphological and molecular analyses of the specimens referred as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[401,516,223,248]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Neacomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[401,516,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Neacomys</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 1 is necessary to test this hypothesis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
